         <abstract id="aspace_94ecbdec257de00846760c4ab1ee26ed">The Joseph W. Angell Papers trace the acquisition of the Thomas Mann Collection for the Yale University Library in 1938 and the preparation of the 1950 exhibit to commemorate the seventy-fifth anniversary of Mann's birth. The papers also document the role of Joseph W. Angell as curator of the Thomas Mann Collection from 1948-1963.</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <persname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no2013033216"
                      source="naf">
               <part>Angell, Joseph Warner, 1908-</part>
            </persname>
         </origination>
    
      </did>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_4f482b716e5b55d648ae397e93e0bb05">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>The papers were the gift of Mrs. Joseph W. Angell in 1990.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_ee562c818f30887bd259c18dfd602cd9">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_eff39505d40a626489f379a717d7fb31">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Joseph Warner Angell Papers (MS 1615). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_7ca6a3a233e8253a9d40ced60e52e83a">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Joseph W. Angell papers consist of correspondence, financial and legal papers, writings, and printed material which trace the acquisition of the Thomas Mann Collection for the Yale University Library in 1938 and the preparation of the 1950 exhibit to commemorate the seventy-fifth anniversary of Mann's birth. The papers also document the role of Joseph W. Angell as curator of the Thomas Mann Collection.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_262a2dcc569815c6af5d355c4caf8bab">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Joseph Warner Angell, Jr. received his B.A. from the College of Wooster in 1930, and his M.A. from the University of Oregon in 1934. At Yale University, Angell was a reader in English from 1936-1939, an assistant professor during the summer of 1947, and curator of the Thomas Mann Collection from 1948-1963.</p>  
      </bioghist>
  
